0","Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1281–":"1281–Overleden","1290–Male":"1290–Overleden","1310–Male":"1310–Overleden","1320–Female":"1320–Overleden","1281–Female":"1281–Overleden","1310":"1310","Abt 1320":"circa 1320","1320":"1320","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1281–":"1281–Deceased","1290–Male":"1290–Deceased","1310–Male":"1310–Deceased","1320–Female":"1320–Deceased","1281–Female":"1281–Deceased","1310":"1310","Abt 1320":"about 1320","1320":"1320","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mallett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Malot</i>, more rarely <i>Malet</i>, a pet form of   Mall  , <i>Mald</i> (i.e. Maud, Matilda) + the diminutive suffix <i>-ot</i> or <i>-et</i>. In post-medieval forms of the surname final <i>-ot</i> was generally altered to <i>-et(t)</i>. Though there are alternative Norman origins (see below), this is the usual source of the English surname.","English: of Norman origin, a nickname from Old French <i>maillet</i> ‘hammer’ (see   Maillet  , compare   Mallet   4), used as a battle weapon. Robert Malet, lord of the Honour of Eye (Suffolk) in 1086, was the son of William Malet of Graville-Sainte-Honorine (Seine-Maritime). The latter is referred to as Gulielmo agnomine <i>Mal(l)eto</i> ‘William, surnamed Mal(l)et’ in the late 11th-century Gesta Guillelmi of William of Poitiers and the early 12th-century Historia Ecclesia of Orderic Vitalis. According to tradition, this surname arose because of William's reputation for bludgeoning his enemies in battle <i>(cum) malleo</i> ‘with the hammer’. The story may be true or it may have been invented to explain the name, in which case see 3 below for an alternative etymology.","English: of Norman origin, from the Old French personal name <i>Malet</i>, a pet form of   Malo  . Compare   Mallet   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Mall","meanings":["English: from the medieval female personal name <i>Mall</i>, a common form of <i>Mald</i> or <i>Maud</i>. See also   Maude   and   Moll  . It had several pet forms; see   Malin  ,   Malkin  , and   Mallet  .","Indian (northern states): from Sanskrit <i>malla</i> ‘strongman, wrestler’."]},{"name":"Maillet","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Yvon, Emile, Ulysse, Alphee, Andre, Jean-Paul, Laurent, Normand, Alban, Alcide, Allain, Antoine.","French:","from Old French <i>maillet</i> ‘mallet’, used as a metonymic occupational name for someone who worked with such an implement, e.g. a smith, or as a nickname for a fearsome warrior (see English   Mallett   2)."]},{"name":"Maillot","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French:","from Old French <i>maillot</i> ‘big mallet’, used as a metonymic occupational name for someone who worked with such an implement, e.g. a smith, and perhaps also as a nickname for a fearsome warrior (see English   Mallett   2). This is the usual form of the surname in France (it is, however, most frequent in Réunion), while in North America it is normally spelled   Mailhot  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs William Mallett was born in 1281, in Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with William Mallett."},"et":{"1281–":"1281–Surnud","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1281–Female":"1281–Surnud","1310":"1310","Abt 1320":"umbes 1320","1320":"1320","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1281–":"1281–Kuollut","1290–Male":"1290–Kuollut","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","1281–Female":"1281–Kuollut","1310":"1310","Abt 1320":"noin 1320","1320":"1320","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1281–":"1281–Décédée","1290–Male":"1290–Décédé","1310–Male":"1310–Décédé","1320–Female":"1320–Décédée","1281–Female":"1281–Décédée","1310":"1310","Abt 1320":"environ 1320","1320":"1320","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Bottisham, Cambridgeshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs William Mallett est née en 1281, à Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils et 1 fille avec William Mallett."},"de":{"1281–":"1281–Verstorben","1290–Male":"